No, this claim is not true. The GDPR does impose direct obligations on processors, but it does not eliminate the need for data processing agreements (DPAs). DPAs are still required under the GDPR because they provide a clear and concise framework for the relationship between controllers and processors, and they help to ensure that both parties are aware of their respective obligations under the GDPR.

A DPA should include the following key elements:

The subject matter and duration of the processing;
The nature and purpose of the processing;
The type of personal data and categories of data subjects;
The obligations of the processor, including security measures and data subject rights;
The obligations of the controller;
The transfer of personal data to a third country or international organization;
The termination of the agreement;
Governing law and jurisdiction;
Dispute resolution.
By having a DPA in place, controllers can be confident that they are meeting their obligations under the GDPR, and processors can be confident that they are working with a controller who is committed to protecting personal data.

No, it is not true that everyone needs a data protection officer (DPO) under GDPR. The GDPR only requires organizations to appoint a DPO if they meet certain criteria. These criteria are set out in Article 37 of the GDPR and include:

The organization is a public authority or body;
The organization's core activities consist of processing data on a large scale;
The organization's regular and systematic monitoring of data subjects on a large scale;
The organization's processing of special categories of personal data or personal data relating to criminal convictions and offenses.
If an organization does not meet any of these criteria, it is not required to appoint a DPO. However, even if an organization is not required to appoint a DPO, it may still choose to do so in order to demonstrate its commitment to data protection and to ensure that it is in compliance with the GDPR.

Here are some of the responsibilities of a DPO:

To advise the organization on data protection matters;
To monitor the organization's compliance with the GDPR;
To conduct data protection impact assessments;
To cooperate with data protection authorities;
To represent the organization in data protection matters.
If you are unsure whether your organization is required to appoint a DPO, you should consult with a data protection lawyer.

