The claim that "Under GDPR, individuals have an absolute right to be forgotten" is not entirely true. The GDPR does give individuals the right to have their personal data erased, but this right is not absolute. There are a number of exceptions to the right to be forgotten, including:

Where the data is necessary for the performance of a public interest task or for the exercise of official authority vested in the controller;
Where the data is necessary for the establishment, exercise or defense of legal claims;
Where the data is necessary for the protection of the vital interests of the data subject or of another natural person;
Where the data has been made public by the data subject and the erasure would affect the right to freedom of expression and information; or
Where the erasure would be contrary to a legal obligation to which the controller is subject.
In addition, the right to be forgotten does not apply to data that has been anonymized or pseudonymized.

Therefore, while the GDPR does give individuals the right to have their personal data erased, this right is not absolute and there are a number of exceptions to it.
